Workshop on Embedding Machine Translation Technology in Digital Libraries

- in conjunction with the Machine Translation Summit XII -

30 August 2009, Ch=E2teau Laurier, Ottawa, Ontario, Canada

DEADLINE  for paper submission 21st June 2009 (0:00 GMT+1)

INVITED SPEAKER : David Bamman (TUFTS University)

Digital libraries become increasingly the main resource for knowledge =20
sharing. Web technology enable that documents physically situated =20
overall in the world, are collected together and can be browsed from =20
anywhere in the world. Semantic Web methods allow additionally =20
knowledge-based reasoning across documents.

A major challenge in this scenario is the multilingual dimension. =20
Cross-lingual information retrieval technologies have the power to =20
manage multilingual content and present to the user. However =20
understanding this content still remains a problem, as long as it is =20
written in a language less or unknown to the user.

Machine Translation and Machine Aided Translation play a major role in =20
making digital libraries available to a broad spectrum of users. Very =20
often users are only interested if the document is really relevant =20
fort them, or if it contains new information. Therefore even partial =20
translation (e.g. of lexical items or syntactic chunks) can be =20
helpful. Digital libraries are on the other hand not only =20
beneficiaries of MT-systems but can provide useful material for =20
improvement of translation technologies. The massive amount of corpora =20
can be used as training sets for language models, sources for =20
improvement of lexicons etc.

The aim of this workshop is to investigate to which extent digital =20
libraries and translation technologies can benefit one of the other =20
and bring together researchers in both domains.

We are looking for original contributions in the following areas:

- Use cases of embedding translation systems in digital libraries
- Translation memories and multilingual lexicons in translation memories
- Evaluation of machine translation systems used for digital libraries =20
(especially robustness against domain change)
- Embedding translation technologies with cross-lingual retrieval in =20
digital libraries
- Usage of digital libraries as training corpus for MT-systems
- Usage of translation technologies in making accessible cultural memory
localization services for digital libraries

We encourage also system demonstrations. Contributions should be sent =20
no later than 21st June 2009 (0:00 GMT + 1) at:

vertan AT informatik DOT uni-hamburg DOT de

Submissions should not exceed 8 pages, and follow the formatting =20
guidelines to be found under http://summitxii.amtaweb.org/  Section =20
Archives /Research Papers


